      <hedline>
        <hl1>London's Restaurant Sports</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr E James Feeley letter on London restaurants (Sept 6 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I heartily agree with your article ''Dinner as Scrum: Could This Be London?'' (Sept. 6), but based on my recent visit there, the major problem is not drinking or shouting, but tobacco smoke. An occasional restaurant will provide a nonsmoking area, but usually I found myself virtually rubbing elbows with people smoking (even cigars) during their meals.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I heartily agree with your article ''Dinner as Scrum: Could This Be London?'' (Sept. 6), but based on my recent visit there, the major problem is not drinking or shouting, but tobacco smoke. An occasional restaurant will provide a nonsmoking area, but usually I found myself virtually rubbing elbows with people smoking (even cigars) during their meals.</p>
        <p>Most absurd, the menus will often solemnly promise that no genetically engineered foods -- which have never been proven to harm a human soul -- are used, and yet customers are exposed to clouds of tobacco smoke. Our surgeon general has documented that second-hand tobacco smoke is associated with severe respiratory disease; are Londoners simply ignorant of this fact or is it a matter of total disdain for the health and comfort of restaurant patrons?</p>
        <p>DR. E. JAMES FEELEY  Fremont, Calif.</p>
      </block>
